metadata.name: pang #226
metadata.description:
Within each of us resides an evolutionary history of primal emotions, yet we often spend our lives dulling and controlling these instincts rather than reveling in them. Art is one of the ways we best express those instincts and intuitions ‚Äì accessing and visualizing their visceral qualities, and releasing our deepest emotions in a way we can share.

pang reflects emotions that take control of our impulses ‚Äì anguish, euphoria, obsession. By using crayon-like marks, the artworks convey the catharsis felt while drawing with a childlike abandon. To capture what gives such marks true feeling, the works deliberate the intrinsic movements, pressures, and angles shaped by hands in various moods. These qualities and their frenetic meanderings represent the infinite possibilities of where the crayon could go next ‚Äì if only we could free ourselves from the layers of control we've built.

The contradictions we struggle with are reflected throughout the works:  in the long, methodical, and mathematical path to creation that yields work that looks fast, free and unrehearsed;  through the randomly-informed computer generation of art that feels human;  and by the depiction of long-standing traditional techniques to help display the conceptual range of a young, innovative art movement still establishing its pivotal place in the canon of art. These tensions parallel the work's underlying concept, accentuating the suspicion that a learned fear of emotional expression might just be the source of our own pang. 

Created in p5.js, pang is inspired by the emotional works and processes of later abstract expressionists such as Cy Twombly and Joan Mitchell ‚Äì as well as contemporary artists like Jos√© Parla.

Press ‚Äòp‚Äô to save as a png. 
Press ‚Äòb‚Äô to render with (or without) a transparent background.
Press 0-9 to render at varying degrees of quality.  0 (lowest quality) to 9 (highest quality, 15000 pixels lengthwise).

metadata.name: Protein Pelt #102
metadata.description:
An incorrectly placed decimal point led to this pattern. A good friend told me it reminded them of protein structures, I found them to look like animal pelts strewn about.

Each "protein" is made up of 100 pelts, random walking around the canvas from the center. Each "pelt" is made of 5 colors sampled from an array of 84 colors.

Press 's' when in live view to save the image.

metadata.name: fx_doughs #4874
Dencity #976
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ‚ù§Ô∏è, code and p5js.

metadata.name: fx_doughs #4358
Art blocks #70
metadata.description:
This is an exploration the possibility of repeatable patterns. There are 6 patterns in total with 120 color palettes. The work is responsive to the height of the viewport, thus a same piece of art may render different result because of different device‚Äôs resolutions. This gives the fun of having different perspectives from different views. Also, the art the BEST IN FULL SCREEN. 

Rarity:
Pattern 0 - 20%
Pattern 1 -5%
Pattern 2 - 15%
Pattern 3 - 30%
Pattern 4 - 15%
Pattern 5 - 20%

- Press "p" to pause/unpause the animation
- Press "s" to save the image

NOTE: there‚Äôs a noise generation, which costs tons of computing power, at the end of the animation. If you find out your browse freezes, or a popup tells you that the page is dead, just BE PATIENT AND WAIT about 0.5-1 minutes for the result :)
